snippet.textDisplay:
That was a really informative video. Not only do I now know how to pronounce Kubernetes (I think you need to double-check what it means in Greek, maybe it is one of those words that can mean different things in different contexts). You can meet its instigator here: https://youtu.be/uMA7qqXIXBk


I can now see the motivation behind them. I struggled to see why they were necessary when you had VMs as a seemingly obvious alternative. Now I know why.


I hope you sprinkle these more in-depth videos into the mix despite any complaints some might have. This information is very relevant and if you work in a large company-I've helped out at Deutsche Bank where I encountered containerisation first being used for running instances of database servers like MySQL and so they are very relevant-Kubernetes and Docker are all over. For myself, I simply didn't factor in their relative ease of launching and reduced system resource needs.


Such videos as these allow those of us -well, whoever wants to include themselves in "us")-who work full time in IT feel your channel is even more credible. Cheers. Mike

snippet.textDisplay:
Absolutely nothing about microservices demands that you run them in a VM or a container. And starting multiple instances of a container on the same machine does not magically grant you more resources. That is, unless the service is badly programmed.
A VM or container is only useful if you want to easily (and usually dynamically) spread your services over multiple machines.

snippet.textDisplay:
Terrible video.
You've made a mess out of deployment strategy; processes in VMs vs. containers. into the whole mess you've added a software architecture decision which is monolithic vs micro-services.
Just to be clean - you can have a microservice or SOA architecture while running processes inside VMs (valid and common strategy).
Kube is one way to do containers in production environments, the are lots of other container orchestrators widely used in production environments.

In addition - the kube nodes probably run on a... VM :D
